<DOC><DOCNO> AP890628-0173 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-06-28-89 1906EST</FILEID><FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     06-28 0447</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0459</SECOND><HEAD>Severe Weather In The Lower Mississippi Valley</HEAD><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   Thunderstorms associated with the remains of Tropical StormAllison spread heavy rain across the lower Mississippi Valley onWednesday, and a band of rain weather extended from that region toNew England.   Baton Rouge, La., had received more than 11 inches of rain in twodays. The Houston area got over a foot of rain from the storm.   Numerous roads were closed in the Baton Rouge area andsurrounding parishes and at least 100 homes were flooded.   Heavier rainfall during the 6 hours up to 2 p.m. EDT included2.53 inches at Cape Girardeau, Mo., and 2.51 inches at Baton Rouge.Paducah, Ky., got 3.57 inches of rain in 3 hours during the morning.   Showers and thunderstorms developing ahead of a cold frontextended from the lower Mississippi Valley through the middleAtlantic Coast region to southern New England.   During the afternoon, a thunderstorm in northern Georgia producedhigh wind which blew down at least one large tree in northern FloydCounty, the National Weather Service said.   Numerous showers and thunderstorms also developed over theFlorida Peninsula during the afternoon.   Thunderstorms extended from southwestern to northeastern Nebraskaduring the afternoon. Morning thunderstorms in north-centralNebraska produced one inch-diameter hail near Stuart, Amelia andBurwell. During the afternoon, a thunderstorm produced hail 2 inchesin diameter at Comstock.   Elsewhere, an approaching storm system brought showers to westernOregon.   Highs reached only the 60s and upper 50s in northeasternMinnesota, northern Wisconsin, Upper Michigan and northern LowerMichigan, and frost and freeze advisories were posted into Thursdaymorning for Upper Michigan.   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 53degrees at Marquette, Mich., to 102 at Phoenix. Wednesday's low inthe Lower 48 states was 36 at West Yellowstone, Mont.   For Thursday, scattered showers and thunderstorms were forecastfrom the eastern half of Texas through Louisiana and Arkansas toFlorida and Georgia. Showers and thunderstorms also were forecastfrom eastern Montana to the western Great Lakes region. A cold frontnearing the northern Pacific Coast was expected to produce scatteredshowers and thunderstorms over Oregon and Washington.   Highs in the 60s were predicted over northern Maine and westernsections of the Great Lakes region; in the 60s and 70s from NewEngland to the Great Lakes region and the northern Ohio Valley; inthe 70s along the California coast and across the Pacific Northwest;in the lower 90s across Florida, Georgia and South Carolina; in the90s across much of the high Plains region, the Rockies and theSouthwest; and above 100 from southwestern Texas to the deserts ofsouthern California.</TEXT></DOC>